that Anon had a problem with it. He enjoyed her touch.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Yeah, but it would be funner than sitting around all night. And it makes for better memories.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Fine, where though?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Oh, I know just the place.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">--------------------</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">The cool night wind passed through Anon’s hair. He took his motorcylce out once he had everything connected again and he tested it. The suspension held, though he’d still upgrade it late. Claire saot on the back clutching him tightly while trying to keep her hood upand being successful for the most part.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Where are we going?” She said into the wind.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“It’s a surprise. “He hoped it would be. They’d been there before, though it was cold and icy. Spring would bring a new shade of green to the park.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Anon stopped the motorcycle. “Is this,” Claire began to ask. “Is this that park we visited during winter?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Yeah.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“What’s there to do here? There’s no more snow.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">Anon laughed. “I don’t know about you, but parks are in season year round. There’s other things to do or we can make it up as we go along.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">Claire smiled at that, though Anon was slowly starting to suspect that she didn’t find most of his jokes funny. Maybe she just liked his laughter.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Come on,” he said, “let’s go inside.” He climbed up the barred fence and hopped down to the other side. Claire followed him and reached the top. She looked down for a second and hopped after him.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">The park was different from when they last visited. New growth spread like wildfire, the trees overhead prospered, the shubbery underneath bloomed like madness, the grass grew thick and green, How it managed to look this nice in the middle of a city as beyond him.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">They found a path and walked down. Claire stopped and smelled the flowers. Anon joined her, “These are nice.” He said.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Yeah.” Claire smelled a big purple flower, letting out a high pitched sneeze.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“That’s so cute,” Anon chuckled as they kept walking until the reached the middle. They sat down on a table.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">Claire looked at him, smiling a little. “Ok, what now?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Whatever we want,” he said. “Do you have anything you you want to do?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">She just looked at him. “Ok, I have an idea. Follow me.” Anon stood up and made his way down one of the paths.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“You say that a lot,” Claire said, following him. “‘Let’s go, come one, follow me.’ And you never say where.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“I do, don’t I?” Anon laughed. “But then it would never be a surprise. If I start doing that, I’d have to start narrating my life in great detail.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“You would do that too, wouldn’t you?” She laughed.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">Anon shrugged and kept walking. “Maybe, maybe not. We’d have to see. I think it would be interesting.” He stopped before a large oak tree with a few lo hanging branches.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“I recgonize this,” Claire commented offhand.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Yeah?” Anon’s eybrow raised.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“It’s where I beat you in that snowball fight.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“That wasn’t a fair win and you know it,” Anon tried to sound hurt but couldn’t help his smile.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“I know that a win is a win.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Uh huh,” he turned to the tree and grabbed a branch. He hauled himself up and grabbed another.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“So what are you doing?” Claire asked, watching him climb the tree.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Leaving you in the dust, apparently. Better catch up.” Anon continued climbing. He looked down and watch her start. She had a little trouble with her footing but she bade it. Spotting a limb nrea the top that looked strong enough to support his weigh, he stopped and sat with his legs on either side. Claire made her way up to him and when within reach, he reach down and pulled her into his lap. His arms wrapped around her waist and he rested his back against the trunk.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Anon? Isn’t this a little to high?” She asked, looking down nervously.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Not high enough if you ask me. We can’t even see over most of the buildings.” He paused a moment. “Besides, I’ve got you. I won’t let you fall.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">Claire leaned back into him, holding her arms. Anon sat there holding her and enjoying the night breeze. She simply enjoyed being there with him. He rested his head on her shoulder.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“Are there always so few stars? She asked.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“In the city.There’s more in the country but all the lights block them out here. I can show you sometime if you want.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“I’d like that. And it’s always like this?”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">“On some darkers nights, say when there’s a blackout or just not enough stars, you can see a few stars.”</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="